Service types, cluster eye-pee, node port, load balancer, and external name.

A service's type controls how reachable it is. There are four values.

Cluster eye-pee is the default. The service gets a virtual eye-pee from the cluster's service range, and it is reachable only from inside the cluster. This is what every internal microservice should be.

Node port makes the service reachable on every node's eye-pee, on a port from the node port range. Node port includes cluster eye-pee, so the virtual eye-pee still exists. From outside, you would hit any node's address on that port. Use it for development clusters and for bare metal clusters that have no load balancer. In a real cloud cluster you almost never expose a node port directly. A load balancer or an ingress sits in front.

Load balancer exposes the service through a cloud provided external load balancer, and it implicitly creates a node port too. The cloud controller manager talks to the cloud's ay-pee-eye, provisions the load balancer, and writes its public address back into the service's status. One caveat. On kind and minikube there is no cloud provider, so a load balancer service stays pending forever, unless you plug in a tool that fakes one for local clusters.

External name is a different beast. It does no proxying at all. It simply makes the service name a dee-en-ess alias, a c-name, pointing at an external host name. So a lookup of the service name returns, say, your managed database's host name, with no virtual eye-pee and no endpoints involved.

The progression is the mental model to keep. Cluster eye-pee for inside, node port for a raw external port, load balancer for a real cloud front door, and external name for a pure dee-en-ess redirect.
